{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"838f4ec8-4a30-48c0-94a6-5b6154f1c571","content":"When `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is set to `1` (via `<startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">` in your app config), it changes how mixed-mode (native/managed) COM components and assemblies built against CLR v2 are loaded:\n\n**What it does:**\n- Binds legacy CLR v2 components (built for .NET 2.0/3.0/3.5) **into the CLR v4 runtime** instead of launching CLR v2 side-by-side.\n- Essentially tells CLR v4 to act as the activation policy for v2-targeted code, similar to how CLR v2 itself behaved (loading everything in-process).\n\n**Effect on runtime selection:**\n- **Without it:** A v2-targeted mixed-mode assembly would require CLR v2 to be loaded (side-by-side with v4), or fail if v2 isn't installed.\n- **With it:** CLR v4 handles those v2 assemblies directly — no side-by-side v2 runtime is loaded. The v4 runtime \"claims\" v2 workloads.\n\n**When you'd see this:**\n- Apps hosting COM components or loading mixed-mode C++/CLI DLLs built against .NET 2.0–3.5.\n- The activation log entry confirms this policy is active for the process.\n\n**Caveat:** This is a .NET Framework-only concept. It has no equivalent in .NET Core/.NET 5+. If you're migrating to modern .NET, this setting can be removed entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c8e43d5a-5fec-4977-9c8c-52f275c864ad","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation logging, specifically about the `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` setting. This is a .NET Framework concept related to how the CLR runtime is selected and activated. Let me answer from my knowledge — this is a well-known .NET Framework configuration topic and doesn't require searching the codebase.","outputTokens":473,"requestId":"1B99:2AB0E:14ACA38:173B888:6A028294"},"id":"8ffa8ccd-b3ec-4814-bcf2-a9592404958f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:30:09.074Z","parentId":"19d56d4a-7806-488c-bae2-518b55b161c8"}
